Hi friends =F0=9F=91=8B,=20
Happy Tuesday and welcome back to Not Boring! Hope your Falls are fantastic=
=2E=20
I haven=E2=80=99t written about crypto for a minute, and a bunch of people =
have asked me whether it=E2=80=99s because I=E2=80=99m less excited about i=
t now than I was before.=20
While I=E2=80=99ve spent more time writing about atoms-based companies and =
exponential curves over the past few months, doing so has actually helped m=
e see crypto=E2=80=99s potential more clearly. If we want to accelerate, we=
=E2=80=99re going to need capitalism to keep up, and I think crypto is uniq=
uely positioned to make that happen.=20
Let=E2=80=99s get to it.=20
Capitalism Onchained
Any technology that is sufficiently valuable in its ideal state will eventu=
ally reach that ideal state.
By ideal state, I mean the imagined end goal or highest potential that tech=
nology could achieve if all the kinks were worked out and it was deployed u=
biquitously.=C2=A0
Understanding the ideal state is maybe the most important thing to do early=
 in the life of a technology, because if that ideal state represents enough=
 value to enough people, the kinks will be worked out and the technology wi=
ll be deployed ubiquitously.=C2=A0
Boom and bust cycles for such technologies are useful noise. The booms are =
useful for attracting resources. The busts are useful for regrouping, fixin=
g problems, and mapping the next leg.=C2=A0=C2=A0
Through any market cycle, the promise of the ideal state acts like a magnet=
, attracting new researchers, entrepreneurs, and investors to improve upon =
the work of those who=E2=80=99ve failed to reach it. If you believe the ide=
al state is possible, then you chalk up previous failures to poor timing or=
 implementation and keep trying new approaches.=C2=A0
AI, AV, and AR/VR are three technologies that wandered through the desert b=
urning billions of dollars for decades and now look to be breaking out. It=
=E2=80=99s capitalism: if the opportunity is big enough if it works, ambiti=
ous people will continue to try to figure out how to make it work. These dr=
eams can=E2=80=99t die, even if thousands of dreamers do on the way.=C2=A0
Recently, there have been fresh calls that crypto is dead. Prices are down,=
 activity is down, people are leaving. I get it. It=E2=80=99s been brutal, =
and even worse, boring. But I=E2=80=99m more convinced now, as of two weeks=
 ago, that crypto is one of those dreams that can=E2=80=99t die.=C2=A0
As soon as I hit send on I, Exponential [ https://substack.com/redirect/19d=
148b2-3685-4862-8c87-1bf1f2373a84?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZ=
jmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], an ode to capitalism, it snapped into place fo=
r me.=C2=A0
Crypto=E2=80=99s ideal state is to make capitalism more effective.
That=E2=80=99s a big claim that risks being overly grandiose. Crypto isn=E2=
=80=99t short on grandiose claims. So I=E2=80=99ll be as specific as possib=
le, laying out my thinking in two parts:
Capitalism is good and capitalism evolves.
How crypto can make capitalism more effective.=C2=A0
Capitalism is Good and Capitalism Evolves
Capitalism works by incentivizing people to act in their own self-interest =
and making it as easy as possible to do so.=C2=A0
Unlike a centrally planned system like socialism, which trusts that a plann=
ing body knows both the problems to work on and the ideal solutions to thos=
e problems, capitalism works by letting anyone bring their best solution to=
 whatever problem they see in the market. Many will fail, some will succeed=
 wildly.
This is a core tenet of capitalism: that incentivizing entrepreneurship and=
 increasing the variance of inputs leads to better outcomes.=C2=A0
To believe my argument that making capitalism more effective would make cry=
pto sufficiently valuable, we need to agree on the two premises: capitalism=
